Chief Complaint/Reason for Admission: Altered mental status, fever

History of Present Illness: 
Margaret Elderly-Example is an 82 y.o. female with a history of vascular dementia, hypertension, atrial fibrillation (on apixaban), and Stage III CKD who was brought to the ED from her Skilled Nursing Facility (SNF) for acute change in mental status.

According to the SNF transfer paperwork and a brief phone conversation with the night nurse at the facility, the patient was in her usual state of health (baseline: oriented to person, occasionally place; ambulatory with a walker) until yesterday evening. She reportedly refused her dinner and was noted to be increasingly somnolent. Overnight, she was found to be incontinent of urine—which was noted to be foul-smelling—and had a tactile fever. Her last recorded vitals at the SNF showed a temperature of 101.4 F and a heart rate of 115.

In the ED, the patient was found to be minimally communicative, only moaning to painful stimuli. She was unable to provide a history. No reports of cough, vomiting, or diarrhea from the facility staff. No history of recent falls or head trauma per facility report. 

Regarding recent antibiotic exposure: Patient completed a course of nitrofurantoin 3 months ago for a documented UTI. No other recent hospitalizations in the last 6 months.

ED Course:
Initial Vitals: 38.6 °C (101.5 °F) | HR (!) 118 | BP 96/58 | RR 22 | SpO2 94 % on room air. | Weight 54.5 kg (120 lb)
Meds and Fluids: Received 2L Normal Saline bolus, IV Vancomycin (renal dosed) + Ceftriaxone. 
Labs: WBC 19.2 (88% neutrophils), Cr 1.92 (baseline 1.1-1.2), UA positive for Leukocyte Esterase, Nitrites, and 50-100 WBCs.
Imaging: CXR negative for acute infiltrate. CT Head (non-contrast) showed no acute intracranial hemorrhage or territorial infarct.

On arrival to the floor, the patient remains somnolent but is now more reactive to tactile stimulation. She is not yet able to follow commands or answer orientation questions.

